00:00:15.582 --> 00:00:18.385 line:71%
Welcome to
"Your Fantastic Mind."

00:00:18.485 --> 00:00:20.420 line:57%
I'm Jaye Watson.
This is a show where

00:00:20.520 --> 00:00:22.689 line:57%
we explore the mysteries
and the science

00:00:22.789 --> 00:00:25.058 line:57%
of the amazing human brain.

00:00:25.158 --> 00:00:27.394 line:71%
Resilience is
a positive word.

00:00:27.494 --> 00:00:30.096 line:71%
It's the capacity to recover
from difficulties,

00:00:30.196 --> 00:00:32.899 line:71%
to bounce back, but
what does resilience mean

00:00:32.999 --> 00:00:35.468 line:71%
when we are talking
about the brain?

00:00:35.568 --> 00:00:38.004 line:71%
This is a story of
a community do-gooder

00:00:38.104 --> 00:00:40.673 line:71%
who almost lost his life
to violence.

00:00:40.774 --> 00:00:43.243 line:71%
Here is his battle
to help his life

00:00:43.343 --> 00:00:46.112 line:71%
and his brain bounce back.

00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:49.182 line:64%
Honey, you're gonna be
a movie star.

00:00:49.282 --> 00:00:50.550 line:64%
Did you know that?

00:00:50.650 --> 00:00:51.584 line:64%
<i> (laughing)</i>

00:00:51.684 --> 00:00:54.054 line:64%
I've always been one
to help other people.

00:00:54.154 --> 00:00:56.189 line:71%
I've done tons of resumes
for people

00:00:56.289 --> 00:00:59.459 line:71%
and just help 'em--
the next step in life

00:00:59.559 --> 00:01:01.461 line:71%
to get 'em forward.

00:01:03.563 --> 00:01:07.100 line:68%
<i> (Jaye Watson)
 At 10 o'clock on the night
 of October 30, 2016,</i>

00:01:07.200 --> 00:01:10.203 line:71%
<i> one of those people
 helped by Russell Erickson</i>

00:01:10.303 --> 00:01:12.972 line:71%
<i> would return to
 his Clarkston home.</i>

00:01:13.073 --> 00:01:15.875 line:71%
<i> Russell would answer the door
 to the person he knew</i>

00:01:15.975 --> 00:01:19.079 line:71%
<i> and had helped, letting
 into his home a man</i>

00:01:19.179 --> 00:01:20.680 line:71%
<i> who, over the next hour,</i>

00:01:20.780 --> 00:01:24.851 line:71%
<i> would rob and almost
 beat him to death.</i>

00:01:24.951 --> 00:01:25.819 line:71%
<i> (Reporter)
 Police say that</i>

00:01:25.919 --> 00:01:27.287 line:71%
<i> when they first came upon
 that victim,</i>

00:01:27.387 --> 00:01:29.489 line:71%
<i> they weren't sure he was
 going to live.</i>

00:01:29.589 --> 00:01:31.257 line:71%
They said that
he managed to escape

00:01:31.357 --> 00:01:32.358 line:71%
through this window here.

00:01:32.459 --> 00:01:34.227 line:71%
When they found him,
he was lying

00:01:34.327 --> 00:01:37.263 line:71%
<i> in a pool of blood
 on the driveway.</i>

00:01:38.898 --> 00:01:41.367 line:71%
I haven't repainted yet
because that's the chemical

00:01:41.468 --> 00:01:43.736 line:71%
<i> they told us to use to clean
 the blood off the walls.</i>

00:01:43.837 --> 00:01:45.505 line:71%
<i> It turns the walls blue.</i>

00:01:45.605 --> 00:01:47.273 line:57%
It was a pretty
traumatic night.

00:01:47.373 --> 00:01:49.776 line:57%
The door was
punched in half,

00:01:49.876 --> 00:01:52.912 line:57%
and then he came in,
and he broke the bed.

00:01:53.012 --> 00:01:54.714 line:57%
I-- this is a different
sleigh bed now

00:01:54.814 --> 00:01:56.382 line:57%
'cause it doesn't have
the posts on it,

00:01:56.483 --> 00:01:58.718 line:57%
but he broke the posts
off of my previous bed

00:01:58.818 --> 00:02:01.788 line:57%
and just clubbed me
with 'em relentlessly

00:02:01.888 --> 00:02:04.124 line:57%
until I'd pass out,
and then, if I'd wake up,

00:02:04.224 --> 00:02:06.960 line:71%
he would beat me again
until I'd pass out again,

00:02:07.060 --> 00:02:08.761 line:71%
and I went through that

00:02:08.862 --> 00:02:11.297 line:71%
for about
an hour and 20 minutes.

00:02:11.397 --> 00:02:12.832 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Erickson finally escaped</i>

00:02:12.932 --> 00:02:15.802 line:71%
<i> through a window, but
 his attacker followed him</i>

00:02:15.902 --> 00:02:18.338 line:71%
<i> and continued to beat him
 in his driveway</i>

00:02:18.438 --> 00:02:21.875 line:71%
<i> where neighbors saw
 and called 911.</i>

00:02:21.975 --> 00:02:24.410 line:71%
<i> A police K-9 unit
 captured the attacker</i>

00:02:24.511 --> 00:02:27.547 line:71%
<i> on a neighbor's porch.</i>

00:02:27.647 --> 00:02:31.918 line:0%
♪♪

00:02:32.018 --> 00:02:34.354 line:71%
<i>(Russell Erickson)
I had a traumatic brain injury.</i>

00:02:36.923 --> 00:02:39.726 line:71%
The brain bleed was the worst
part of all my injuries.

00:02:39.826 --> 00:02:42.562 line:71%
<i> My eye sockets were both
 broken, and my nose was</i>

00:02:42.662 --> 00:02:45.298 line:71%
<i> badly displaced, and I had
 a torn rotator cuff</i>

00:02:45.398 --> 00:02:47.800 line:71%
<i> on the left side,
 and then I had</i>

00:02:47.901 --> 00:02:50.470 line:71%
broken ribs
on both sides.

00:02:50.570 --> 00:02:53.740 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Erickson spent four days
 on life support.</i>

00:02:53.840 --> 00:02:56.609 line:68%
<i> (Dr. David Burke)
 He had blunt trauma with
 someone striking his head</i>

00:02:56.709 --> 00:03:00.146 line:71%
<i> repeatedly with a, um,
 blunt object, so he had</i>

00:03:00.246 --> 00:03:02.715 line:71%
bruising and bleeding
in the brain and

00:03:02.815 --> 00:03:05.451 line:71%
<i> swelling of the brain.</i>

00:03:06.986 --> 00:03:09.289 line:71%
<i> And there's tearing forces
 that occur, uh,</i>

00:03:09.389 --> 00:03:12.792 line:71%
<i> within the small neurons
 or axons of the brain,</i>

00:03:12.892 --> 00:03:15.628 line:71%
<i> and, therefore, individual
 fibers of the brain</i>

00:03:15.728 --> 00:03:19.599 line:71%
<i> are torn and damaged
 permanently.</i>

00:03:19.699 --> 00:03:20.934 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dr. David Burke is</i>

00:03:21.034 --> 00:03:24.270 line:71%
<i>the brain rehabilitation expert
who treated Erickson.</i>

00:03:24.370 --> 00:03:25.638 line:71%
<i>(Dr. Burke)
During that recovery mechanism,</i>

00:03:25.738 --> 00:03:27.106 line:57%
swelling will occur.

00:03:27.207 --> 00:03:30.343 line:57%
Uh, with the swelling,
uh, comes a decrease

00:03:30.443 --> 00:03:33.213 line:57%
in oxygen to parts of
the brain that evolves

00:03:33.313 --> 00:03:36.182 line:71%
<i> over time, and, therefore,
 you can suffocate</i>

00:03:36.282 --> 00:03:38.418 line:71%
<i> some of the brain
 in that early stages.</i>

00:03:38.518 --> 00:03:42.322 line:71%
<i>You can squeeze the life out of
some of the brain tissue</i>

00:03:42.422 --> 00:03:46.092 line:71%
<i> from the swelling because
 it's got nowhere to go.</i>

00:03:46.192 --> 00:03:48.127 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Parts of the brain can die,</i>

00:03:48.228 --> 00:03:49.829 line:71%
<i> but Burke says
 the understanding of</i>

00:03:49.929 --> 00:03:52.332 line:71%
<i> the regenerative capacity
 of the brain</i>

00:03:52.432 --> 00:03:54.200 line:71%
<i> has shifted
 over the years.</i>

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:56.769 line:71%
<i> Take axons, the small nerves
 in the brain</i>

00:03:56.869 --> 00:03:59.239 line:71%
<i> that send signals
 to its destination,</i>

00:03:59.339 --> 00:04:01.341 line:71%
<i> like making
 your fingers move.</i>

00:04:01.441 --> 00:04:03.076 line:71%
When I was in med school,
we were told that's it.

00:04:03.176 --> 00:04:06.813 line:71%
They don't-- the-the axons
do not regrow.

00:04:06.913 --> 00:04:10.750 line:71%
But we now know that
the axons do regrow, um,

00:04:10.850 --> 00:04:13.820 line:71%
but probably not
in sufficient quantity

00:04:13.920 --> 00:04:17.090 line:71%
to regrow portions
of the brain

00:04:17.190 --> 00:04:18.591 line:71%
that are damaged,
and, therefore,

00:04:18.691 --> 00:04:21.194 line:71%
the reorganization
of existing tissue is

00:04:21.294 --> 00:04:23.863 line:71%
very much the recovery.

00:04:23.963 --> 00:04:25.198 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Russell did not lose function</i>

00:04:25.298 --> 00:04:27.567 line:71%
<i> in his limbs, but
 because he was beaten</i>

00:04:27.667 --> 00:04:30.570 line:71%
<i> all about his head,
 his injury to his brain</i>

00:04:30.670 --> 00:04:32.805 line:71%
<i> involved many areas
 that were no longer</i>

00:04:32.905 --> 00:04:34.641 line:71%
<i> functioning like they should.</i>

00:04:34.741 --> 00:04:38.478 line:64%
<i> He had attention issues
 common to those with TBIs.</i>

00:04:38.578 --> 00:04:43.082 line:64%
<i> He had severe vertigo, sleep,
 memory, and speech issues.</i>

00:04:43.182 --> 00:04:46.352 line:64%
<i> He could move about the world
 seemingly normal,</i>

00:04:46.452 --> 00:04:50.223 line:71%
<i> but nothing was
 as it had been before.</i>

00:04:50.323 --> 00:04:51.324 line:71%
<i> (Dr. Burke)
 There are things we can do</i>

00:04:51.424 --> 00:04:53.960 line:71%
<i> to accelerate
 the healing of the brain.</i>

00:04:54.060 --> 00:04:55.061 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Medications serve as</i>

00:04:55.161 --> 00:04:57.463 line:71%
<i> a foundation for the healing
 of the brain.</i>

00:04:57.563 --> 00:04:59.866 line:71%
<i> They can help
 those attention issues,</i>

00:04:59.966 --> 00:05:03.102 line:71%
<i> altered sleep cycles,
 debilitating headaches,</i>

00:05:03.202 --> 00:05:05.471 line:71%
<i> dizziness, forgetfulness,
 depression, even</i>

00:05:05.571 --> 00:05:09.142 line:71%
<i> thinking that feels slower--
 all problems</i>

00:05:09.242 --> 00:05:12.011 line:71%
<i> caused by
 the trauma to the brain.</i>

00:05:12.111 --> 00:05:15.948 line:68%
<i> (Dr. Burke)
 Any problem with
 forgetting mid-sentence?</i>

00:05:16.049 --> 00:05:17.583 line:57%
<i>When I get tired
in the afternoon,</i>

00:05:17.684 --> 00:05:20.053 line:57%
I will have a hard time
pulling a word

00:05:20.153 --> 00:05:22.522 line:57%
out of my memory that
I'm wanting to say.

00:05:22.622 --> 00:05:23.523 line:64%
(Dr. Burke)
Okay.

00:05:23.623 --> 00:05:25.091 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Medications support the brain</i>

00:05:25.191 --> 00:05:29.028 line:71%
and the person, making intense
cognitive and physical rehab

00:05:29.128 --> 00:05:30.496 line:71%
more effective.

00:05:30.596 --> 00:05:31.531 line:71%
Three.

00:05:31.631 --> 00:05:33.700 line:71%
<i> (Dr. Burke)
 The more you attempt to do</i>

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:37.804 line:71%
what h-has been damaged,
uh, the more likely

00:05:37.904 --> 00:05:39.305 line:71%
<i> the brain will reorganize.</i>

00:05:39.405 --> 00:05:42.342 line:71%
<i> And, in Russell's case,
 he's the most motivated guy</i>

00:05:42.442 --> 00:05:43.710 line:71%
<i> that you'll meet.</i>

00:05:43.810 --> 00:05:45.478 line:71%
Face the mirror.
Ready?

00:05:45.578 --> 00:05:47.513 line:71%
Step up.

00:05:47.613 --> 00:05:49.082 line:71%
Good, and back.

00:05:49.182 --> 00:05:52.051 line:71%
<i>And turning your head
right and left five times.</i>

00:05:52.151 --> 00:05:53.019 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 The work to get back</i>

00:05:53.119 --> 00:05:54.954 line:71%
<i> what was lost...</i>

00:05:55.054 --> 00:05:56.889 line:57%
Excuse me.

00:05:55.054 --> 00:05:56.889 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Is hard.</i>

00:05:56.989 --> 00:05:58.191 line:71%
All right,
five more seconds.

00:05:58.291 --> 00:05:59.258 line:71%
(Jaye)
There is physical...

00:05:59.359 --> 00:06:00.626 line:71%
Gonna give you
a little more resistance.

00:06:00.727 --> 00:06:01.394 line:71%
Mm-hmm.

00:06:01.494 --> 00:06:04.030 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Occupational...</i>

00:06:04.130 --> 00:06:05.798 line:71%
<i> And speech therapy.</i>

00:06:05.898 --> 00:06:08.000 line:71%
You're right on with that.

00:06:08.101 --> 00:06:11.371 line:71%
You don't wanna be labeled
as a brain injured person.

00:06:11.471 --> 00:06:12.372 line:71%
Yes.

00:06:12.472 --> 00:06:16.542 line:71%
You are a person who
had a brain injury.

00:06:16.642 --> 00:06:18.111 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 There is vestibular therapy</i>

00:06:18.211 --> 00:06:19.912 line:71%
<i> to improve vertigo.</i>

00:06:20.012 --> 00:06:21.280 line:71%
<i> (Therapist)
 And look at the red light.</i>

00:06:21.381 --> 00:06:22.115 line:71%
Mm-hmm.

00:06:22.215 --> 00:06:30.723 line:0%
♪♪

00:06:30.823 --> 00:06:31.924 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Almost two years after</i>

00:06:32.024 --> 00:06:36.028 line:71%
the night he nearly died,
Russell has his life back.

00:06:36.129 --> 00:06:40.133 line:71%
He returned to his job at 3M
just months after the attack.

00:06:42.301 --> 00:06:46.139 line:71%
So, how is it that two people
can have the same injury,

00:06:46.239 --> 00:06:49.609 line:71%
but one will recover
better than the other?

00:06:49.709 --> 00:06:51.644 line:71%
One reason is genetics.

00:06:51.744 --> 00:06:55.715 line:57%
A great example is,
uh, the boxing careers

00:06:55.815 --> 00:06:57.383 line:71%
of Muhammad Ali
and Joe Frazier.

00:06:57.483 --> 00:07:00.653 line:71%
You know, arguably
two of the best fighters,

00:07:00.753 --> 00:07:05.091 line:71%
<i> uh, ever, and they arguably,
 um, punched each other</i>

00:07:05.191 --> 00:07:09.762 line:71%
the same amount of time,
same amount of, you know,

00:07:09.862 --> 00:07:14.066 line:71%
trauma to each, but
Joe Frazier didn't seem

00:07:14.167 --> 00:07:17.904 line:71%
phased by it, and Muhammad Ali
got Parkinson's disease

00:07:18.004 --> 00:07:21.741 line:71%
and was, you know,
when I met him a few years ago,

00:07:21.841 --> 00:07:24.377 line:71%
unable to speak,
was having trouble walking,

00:07:24.477 --> 00:07:26.412 line:71%
uh, had really deteriorated.

00:07:26.512 --> 00:07:28.281 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 In patients like
 Russell Erickson, there is</i>

00:07:28.381 --> 00:07:30.750 line:71%
<i> something else that is
 harder to measure,</i>

00:07:30.850 --> 00:07:32.985 line:71%
<i> something that
 does not show up in images</i>

00:07:33.085 --> 00:07:36.289 line:71%
<i> of the brain or in
 measurements of the body.</i>

00:07:36.389 --> 00:07:39.459 line:71%
I was given a little stone,
and put it in your pocket,

00:07:39.559 --> 00:07:41.994 line:71%
<i> and every time you touch it,
 you think of something</i>

00:07:42.094 --> 00:07:43.362 line:71%
<i> to be grateful for.</i>

00:07:43.463 --> 00:07:46.098 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 He has a supply
 of gratitude stones</i>

00:07:46.199 --> 00:07:49.635 line:71%
<i> for himself and just about
 everybody he meets.</i>

00:07:49.735 --> 00:07:51.304 line:71%
<i> (Russell)
 For the longest time,</i>

00:07:51.404 --> 00:07:53.439 line:71%
<i> I looked at these pictures,
 and then I actually</i>

00:07:53.539 --> 00:07:56.008 line:71%
put 'em away, so I wouldn't
start relating to

00:07:56.108 --> 00:07:57.777 line:71%
that's who I am.

00:07:57.877 --> 00:07:59.479 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 He put those photos away,</i>

00:07:59.579 --> 00:08:01.314 line:71%
<i> focusing on healing.</i>

00:08:01.414 --> 00:08:02.515 line:71%
You back for
some more pettin'?

00:08:02.615 --> 00:08:04.617 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Letting go of the trauma.</i>

00:08:04.717 --> 00:08:06.586 line:71%
<i> A conversation with
 a police officer</i>

00:08:06.686 --> 00:08:10.223 line:71%
<i> just days after he was
 attacked illustrates that.</i>

00:08:10.323 --> 00:08:12.658 line:71%
<i> (Russell)
 He asked me, "How do you feel</i>

00:08:12.758 --> 00:08:15.695 line:71%
<i> "about this guy
 who did this to you?"</i>

00:08:15.795 --> 00:08:18.030 line:57%
And I said, "Well,"

00:08:18.130 --> 00:08:20.967 line:57%
I said, uh,
"Between you and me,

00:08:21.067 --> 00:08:25.505 line:71%
"I have to forgive him
completely and-- because I need

00:08:25.605 --> 00:08:28.508 line:71%
"all my energy for healing,
and if I hold a grudge

00:08:28.608 --> 00:08:32.278 line:71%
"against him, then that's gonna
rob me of my healing."

00:08:35.515 --> 00:08:36.415 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Erickson still helps</i>

00:08:36.516 --> 00:08:38.551 line:71%
<i> those in need, but
 he now meets them</i>

00:08:38.651 --> 00:08:40.686 line:71%
<i> at public places,
 and his home has</i>

00:08:40.786 --> 00:08:42.788 line:71%
<i> a camera surveillance system.</i>

00:08:42.889 --> 00:08:45.992 line:57%
One thing that I think is
critical is that

00:08:46.092 --> 00:08:50.897 line:57%
people stop looking
in the rear view mirror

00:08:50.997 --> 00:08:52.164 line:57%
and look ahead.
I say, you know,

00:08:52.265 --> 00:08:53.666 line:71%
<i> you can't drive through life
 if you're looking</i>

00:08:53.766 --> 00:08:55.234 line:71%
in the rear view mirror,
and if they're always

00:08:55.334 --> 00:08:58.170 line:71%
looking at what they lost
rather than ahead

00:08:58.271 --> 00:09:02.475 line:71%
of what they can acquire,
then their recovery is slow.

00:09:02.575 --> 00:09:05.945 line:71%
I think Russell's like,
"let's go," you know?

00:09:06.045 --> 00:09:10.483 line:71%
He doesn't have rear view
mirrors in his car.

00:09:10.583 --> 00:09:11.484 line:71%
<i> (chuckles)</i>

00:09:11.584 --> 00:09:14.520 line:71%
He took 'em off
a long time ago.

00:09:14.620 --> 00:09:16.789 line:71%
<i>(Jaye)
Despite all he has been through,</i>

00:09:16.889 --> 00:09:18.658 line:71%
<i> the man with
 rocks in his pockets</i>

00:09:18.758 --> 00:09:21.861 line:71%
<i> and a smile on his face
 will tell you</i>

00:09:21.961 --> 00:09:25.131 line:71%
<i> he's one of the luckiest
 guys around.</i>

00:09:25.231 --> 00:09:27.300 line:71%
You can come out on the other
side just as blessed

00:09:27.400 --> 00:09:30.303 line:71%
or more blessed even though
you go through

00:09:30.403 --> 00:09:32.371 line:71%
<i> hard experiences.</i>

00:09:32.471 --> 00:09:40.913 line:0%
♪♪

00:09:41.013 --> 00:09:42.281 line:71%
So, the one thing
this week is

00:09:42.381 --> 00:09:43.883 line:71%
something that could
reduce your risk

00:09:43.983 --> 00:09:47.119 line:71%
of type two diabetes,
cardiovascular disease,

00:09:47.219 --> 00:09:50.923 line:71%
premature death, stress,
even high blood pressure.

00:09:51.023 --> 00:09:54.727 line:71%
That one thing is
getting out in nature.

00:09:54.827 --> 00:09:57.964 line:71%
<i> Scientists looked at
 global data from 140 studies</i>

00:09:58.064 --> 00:10:02.168 line:71%
<i> involving 290 million people
 from 20 different countries,</i>

00:10:02.268 --> 00:10:04.136 line:71%
<i> including the U.S.,
 looking to see</i>

00:10:04.236 --> 00:10:07.340 line:71%
if nature provides
a legitimate health boost.

00:10:07.440 --> 00:10:09.041 line:71%
They analyzed the health
of people with

00:10:09.141 --> 00:10:12.345 line:71%
<i> the least access to nature
 with those with the most,</i>

00:10:12.445 --> 00:10:13.779 line:71%
and those with the most,
well, they had

00:10:13.879 --> 00:10:17.283 line:71%
<i> lower incidences of several
 conditions and diseases.</i>

00:10:17.383 --> 00:10:19.251 line:71%
<i> They also had
 lower blood pressure,</i>

00:10:19.352 --> 00:10:21.988 line:71%
<i> lower heart rate,
 lower stress.</i>

00:10:22.088 --> 00:10:24.857 line:71%
They even slept longer.
One of the more interesting

00:10:24.957 --> 00:10:28.260 line:71%
findings is that being in nature
dramatically reduces

00:10:28.361 --> 00:10:31.030 line:71%
people's levels
of salivary cortisol,

00:10:31.130 --> 00:10:33.733 line:71%
a physiological marker
of stress.

00:10:33.833 --> 00:10:35.735 line:71%
This is one treatment that
you don't need

00:10:35.835 --> 00:10:37.970 line:71%
a prescription
from your doctor.

00:10:39.238 --> 00:10:42.642 line:71%
It is the most famous dance
to come out of Argentina.

00:10:42.742 --> 00:10:45.111 line:71%
Tango-- a partner dance
that emphasizes

00:10:45.211 --> 00:10:47.079 line:71%
vibrant and
playful movement

00:10:47.179 --> 00:10:49.849 line:71%
and lots of improvisation.

00:10:49.949 --> 00:10:52.084 line:71%
But tango is also
becoming known as

00:10:52.184 --> 00:10:55.655 line:71%
a powerful tool for patients
with Parkinson's disease.

00:10:55.755 --> 00:10:59.625 line:71%
This story is about
a Parkinson's brain on tango.

00:10:59.725 --> 00:11:02.361 line:0%
♪♪

00:11:02.461 --> 00:11:05.031 line:71%
I just saw her, and she just
did somethin' to me.

00:11:05.131 --> 00:11:06.565 line:71%
Somethin' just went ca-clunk.

00:11:06.666 --> 00:11:08.701 line:71%
<i> (laughing)</i>

00:11:08.801 --> 00:11:10.603 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 The disco was Christy's</i>

00:11:10.703 --> 00:11:13.305 line:71%
<i> in Cincinnati, Ohio,
 and the woman who</i>

00:11:13.406 --> 00:11:17.009 line:71%
<i> made something go ca-clunk
 inside Lee Reaves</i>

00:11:17.109 --> 00:11:18.544 line:71%
<i> was Jere.</i>

00:11:18.644 --> 00:11:19.645 line:71%
<i> (Lee Reaves)
 I kept begging her</i>

00:11:19.745 --> 00:11:21.514 line:71%
<i> to marry me, marry me,
 marry me, marry me,</i>

00:11:21.614 --> 00:11:24.450 line:71%
and she kept saying,
"No, no, no."

00:11:24.550 --> 00:11:27.486 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 The "yes" came 34 years ago.</i>

00:11:27.586 --> 00:11:29.455 line:71%
And we danced our way
through our marriage.

00:11:29.555 --> 00:11:31.290 line:71%
<i> (laughing)</i>

00:11:31.390 --> 00:11:32.391 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 That was before</i>

00:11:32.491 --> 00:11:35.261 line:71%
<i> Lee, a mechanical engineer,
 had a stroke.</i>

00:11:35.361 --> 00:11:37.930 line:71%
<i> It was before Jere,
 a registered nurse,</i>

00:11:38.030 --> 00:11:41.400 line:71%
<i> noticed a change
 in her body.</i>

00:11:41.500 --> 00:11:44.236 line:57%
I didn't really feel anything
going on

00:11:44.336 --> 00:11:47.273 line:57%
except just a twitching
in my pinky,

00:11:47.373 --> 00:11:49.341 line:71%
sorta like a-- like
a tick you might get

00:11:49.442 --> 00:11:51.210 line:71%
in-in the face.

00:11:51.310 --> 00:11:52.945 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 That twitching pinky led to</i>

00:11:53.045 --> 00:11:56.015 line:71%
<i> a diagnosis of
 Parkinson's disease.</i>

00:11:56.115 --> 00:11:56.916 line:71%
<i>(Lee)
It was kinda devastating</i>

00:11:57.016 --> 00:11:58.684 line:57%
at first, you know?
Well, I dunno

00:11:58.784 --> 00:12:00.286 line:57%
if it's devastating.
It was just somethin'-somethin'

00:12:00.386 --> 00:12:03.155 line:57%
to-to get your arms around.

00:12:03.255 --> 00:12:04.790 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Doctors don't know what causes</i>

00:12:04.890 --> 00:12:07.626 line:0%
<i> Parkinson's disease,
 a slowly progressive</i>

00:12:07.727 --> 00:12:09.662 line:0%
<i> neurological disorder
 that is caused by</i>

00:12:09.762 --> 00:12:12.498 line:0%
<i> degeneration of neurons
 in the brain.</i>

00:12:12.598 --> 00:12:15.334 line:71%
<i> Dr. Stewart Factor is
 the Director of the Movement</i>

00:12:15.434 --> 00:12:18.537 line:71%
<i> Disorders Program
 at Emory Brain Health Center.</i>

00:12:18.637 --> 00:12:22.374 line:57%
The main neurons that die
are dopamine neurons,

00:12:22.475 --> 00:12:25.211 line:57%
and, uh, all the treatments
that we have--

00:12:25.311 --> 00:12:27.613 line:57%
nearly all the treatments
are for replacement

00:12:27.713 --> 00:12:29.882 line:71%
of dopamine in the brain.

00:12:29.982 --> 00:12:31.383 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Among its many jobs,</i>

00:12:31.484 --> 00:12:34.186 line:71%
<i> dopamine impacts
 brain processes</i>

00:12:34.286 --> 00:12:36.689 line:71%
<i> that control movement.</i>

00:12:36.789 --> 00:12:39.391 line:71%
It's defined by
motor symptoms-- tremor,

00:12:39.492 --> 00:12:44.196 line:71%
stiffness, slowness, walking
and balance problems.

00:12:44.296 --> 00:12:47.867 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 It's been ten years
 since Jere's diagnosis.</i>

00:12:47.967 --> 00:12:49.101 line:71%
<i> (Jere)
 I'm doing pretty good.</i>

00:12:49.201 --> 00:12:51.670 line:71%
<i> I think there's-- it's
 advancing a little bit now.</i>

00:12:51.771 --> 00:12:54.940 line:71%
<i> It's getting harder to, like,
 follow the lines.</i>

00:12:55.040 --> 00:12:56.542 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 She still paints,</i>

00:12:56.642 --> 00:12:59.078 line:71%
<i> the latest a family tree.</i>

00:12:59.178 --> 00:13:02.448 line:71%
I'm going to put names
on the big leaves

00:13:02.548 --> 00:13:04.150 line:71%
of the different
family members.

00:13:04.250 --> 00:13:05.951 line:71%
Will you tie a knot
in there?

00:13:06.051 --> 00:13:07.453 line:71%
Yeah.

00:13:07.553 --> 00:13:08.521 line:71%
Thank you.

00:13:08.621 --> 00:13:12.458 line:71%
<i> I sew, and I can't
 do as neat a job now.</i>

00:13:12.558 --> 00:13:16.328 line:71%
<i> Uh, writing is terrible.</i>

00:13:16.428 --> 00:13:18.664 line:71%
<i> You can barely read it.</i>

00:13:18.764 --> 00:13:21.467 line:71%
And my voice
has been modulating

00:13:21.567 --> 00:13:23.702 line:71%
like almost not there.

00:13:23.803 --> 00:13:26.005 line:64%
<i> (Jaye)
 Walking has replaced running.</i>

00:13:26.105 --> 00:13:29.208 line:64%
Last year, Jere broke her hip
in a fall.

00:13:29.308 --> 00:13:33.879 line:64%
Despite the struggles,
there is one constant.

00:13:33.979 --> 00:13:35.214 line:71%
<i> (Instructor)
 All right, everyone,</i>

00:13:35.314 --> 00:13:37.683 line:71%
<i> when you get a chance, grab
 a partner and start dancing.</i>

00:13:37.783 --> 00:13:39.318 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 It's less nightclub</i>

00:13:39.418 --> 00:13:42.721 line:57%
<i> and more high school gym,
 but make no mistake.</i>

00:13:42.822 --> 00:13:46.725 line:57%
<i> The gym at the VA in Atlanta
 is tango central.</i>

00:13:46.826 --> 00:13:50.629 line:64%
Five, six, ready, and...

00:13:50.729 --> 00:13:54.266 line:64%
<i> T-A-N-G-O</i>

00:13:54.366 --> 00:13:58.971 line:71%
<i> and T-A-N-G-O.</i>

00:13:59.071 --> 00:14:00.339 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Parkinson's patients are</i>

00:14:00.439 --> 00:14:02.808 line:71%
<i> paired with volunteers,
 from grad students</i>

00:14:02.908 --> 00:14:05.244 line:71%
<i> to dancers
 in the community.</i>

00:14:05.344 --> 00:14:06.779 line:71%
Am I messin' up
too much?

00:14:06.879 --> 00:14:08.914 line:71%
No, we're doing great.

00:14:10.015 --> 00:14:11.550 line:71%
<i> (Lee)
 I like it-- it's fun.</i>

00:14:11.650 --> 00:14:14.320 line:71%
<i> You know, you meet a lotta--
 a lotta cool people.</i>

00:14:16.288 --> 00:14:17.256 line:64%
<i> (Jaye)
 Lee and Jere have come</i>

00:14:17.356 --> 00:14:19.491 line:64%
<i> twice a week
 for a few years,</i>

00:14:19.592 --> 00:14:21.627 line:64%
<i> not just because it's fun,
 but because</i>

00:14:21.727 --> 00:14:23.562 line:64%
<i> it is helping Jere.</i>

00:14:23.662 --> 00:14:25.264 line:71%
<i> (Jere)
 I've noticed a difference.</i>

00:14:25.364 --> 00:14:29.401 line:57%
<i> It organizes, uh,
 movement better,</i>

00:14:29.501 --> 00:14:33.072 line:57%
<i> and it-- with the steps
 for tango,</i>

00:14:33.172 --> 00:14:35.908 line:57%
you have to switch,
uh, your thinking.

00:14:36.008 --> 00:14:37.810 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Emory Assistant Professor
 of Medicine</i>

00:14:37.910 --> 00:14:40.646 line:71%
<i> and VA Research Scientist
 Dr. Madeleine Hackney</i>

00:14:40.746 --> 00:14:42.581 line:71%
<i> is the tango instructor.</i>

00:14:42.681 --> 00:14:46.452 line:71%
T-A-N-G-O.

00:14:46.552 --> 00:14:48.554 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 She is also a former</i>

00:14:48.654 --> 00:14:50.656 line:71%
professional dancer.

00:14:50.756 --> 00:14:52.458 line:68%
(Dr. Madeline Hackney)
And I knew that I was
especially interested

00:14:52.558 --> 00:14:55.494 line:71%
in the way the brain
controls movement.

00:14:55.594 --> 00:14:57.696 line:71%
<i>(Jaye)
It's an unconventional approach</i>

00:14:57.796 --> 00:15:00.933 line:71%
<i> with an unconventional
 lead scientist.</i>

00:15:01.033 --> 00:15:02.067 line:71%
<i> But what the tango can do</i>

00:15:02.167 --> 00:15:05.137 line:71%
<i> for people with Parkinson's
 is significant.</i>

00:15:05.237 --> 00:15:07.840 line:71%
I had this idea that
dance might be

00:15:07.940 --> 00:15:10.976 line:71%
something that could help
people to move better

00:15:11.076 --> 00:15:13.245 line:71%
<i> and overcome various
 injuries, because</i>

00:15:13.345 --> 00:15:17.516 line:71%
<i> dancers think about
 movement so deeply.</i>

00:15:17.616 --> 00:15:18.651 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 There had already been</i>

00:15:18.751 --> 00:15:21.287 line:71%
<i> some research on
 the effects of tango.</i>

00:15:21.387 --> 00:15:24.723 line:57%
There was one, um,
that had shown that

00:15:24.823 --> 00:15:27.192 line:57%
frail older adults,
if they participated in

00:15:27.293 --> 00:15:30.129 line:57%
Argentine tango,
had improved

00:15:30.229 --> 00:15:34.033 line:57%
in complex walking tasks
afterwards, comparison

00:15:34.133 --> 00:15:37.336 line:71%
<i>to a-an exercise control group,
and so that was like</i>

00:15:37.436 --> 00:15:39.471 line:71%
a little piece of--
kernel of evidence that,

00:15:39.571 --> 00:15:41.807 line:71%
okay, tango, interesting.

00:15:41.907 --> 00:15:43.142 line:71%
<i> And then there was another
 piece of evidence</i>

00:15:43.242 --> 00:15:44.443 line:71%
<i> that showed that
 while people were lying</i>

00:15:44.543 --> 00:15:46.979 line:71%
<i> in a positron emission
 tomography, a PET scanner,</i>

00:15:47.079 --> 00:15:48.614 line:71%
<i> if they were doing
 tango-like movements</i>

00:15:48.714 --> 00:15:52.051 line:71%
to a very rhythmic beat,
there was increased

00:15:52.151 --> 00:15:55.020 line:71%
<i> activation in the putamen
 of the basal ganglia,</i>

00:15:55.120 --> 00:15:57.890 line:71%
<i> which is the part
 of the brain that is</i>

00:15:57.990 --> 00:16:00.893 line:71%
<i> most impacted by
 Parkinson's disease.</i>

00:16:00.993 --> 00:16:02.094 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 Dr. Hackney's first</i>

00:16:02.194 --> 00:16:04.797 line:71%
<i> pilot study on tango for
 Parkinson's patients</i>

00:16:04.897 --> 00:16:06.465 line:71%
<i> was 12 years ago.</i>

00:16:06.565 --> 00:16:09.501 line:71%
<i> She modified the dance
 and the steps to make it</i>

00:16:09.601 --> 00:16:12.404 line:71%
<i> safe yet hopefully effective.</i>

00:16:12.504 --> 00:16:13.472 line:71%
<i> (Dr. Hackney)
 First of all, we looked at</i>

00:16:13.572 --> 00:16:16.475 line:71%
<i> 20 hours of tango
 over a 12-week period</i>

00:16:16.575 --> 00:16:20.212 line:71%
<i> versus 20 hours
 of a chair exercise class,</i>

00:16:20.312 --> 00:16:22.982 line:71%
<i> which is the traditional class
 that was offered at the time.</i>

00:16:23.082 --> 00:16:26.285 line:71%
<i> Improved balance
 and gait parameters,</i>

00:16:26.385 --> 00:16:28.554 line:71%
<i> so it improved
 balance and walking.</i>

00:16:28.654 --> 00:16:29.922 line:0%
<i> (Jaye)
 Hackney's study showed that</i>

00:16:30.022 --> 00:16:33.258 line:0%
<i> after the class, tango dancers
 with Parkinson's</i>

00:16:33.359 --> 00:16:36.628 line:0%
<i> were able to walk further,
 faster, and longer</i>

00:16:36.729 --> 00:16:38.197 line:0%
<i> than before the class.</i>

00:16:38.297 --> 00:16:41.200 line:0%
<i> Standard clinical motor exams
 to measure balance</i>

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:45.771 line:0%
<i> also showed improvements
 that were also retained.</i>

00:16:45.871 --> 00:16:47.639 line:57%
So, does it have to
be tango?

00:16:47.740 --> 00:16:50.476 line:57%
Well, Hackney says that
the fox trot and the waltz

00:16:50.576 --> 00:16:53.812 line:57%
are just as effective,
with one difference...

00:16:53.912 --> 00:16:55.080 line:57%
this.
Tango patients were able

00:16:55.180 --> 00:16:57.282 line:57%
to get up from
a chair and walk

00:16:57.383 --> 00:16:58.917 line:57%
more easily
and quickly.

00:16:59.018 --> 00:17:01.286 line:71%
That is no small feat
in a disease

00:17:01.387 --> 00:17:04.089 line:71%
marked by mobility issues.

00:17:04.189 --> 00:17:07.326 line:71%
<i> Hackney says the improvisation
 that tango allows</i>

00:17:07.426 --> 00:17:10.562 line:71%
<i> is another plus
 for patients.</i>

00:17:10.662 --> 00:17:13.899 line:71%
<i> Functional MRIs, which look at
 blood flow in the brain</i>

00:17:13.999 --> 00:17:16.869 line:71%
<i> to detect areas of activity,
 are now being used</i>

00:17:16.969 --> 00:17:19.805 line:71%
<i> to learn what brain network
 scenarios change</i>

00:17:19.905 --> 00:17:21.607 line:71%
<i> after dance rehabilitation</i>

00:17:21.707 --> 00:17:24.610 line:71%
<i> in people with
 Parkinson's disease.</i>

00:17:24.710 --> 00:17:27.513 line:71%
<i> There is no definitive answer
 yet, but Hackney thinks</i>

00:17:27.613 --> 00:17:31.316 line:71%
<i> the findings will confirm
 what she believes.</i>

00:17:31.417 --> 00:17:32.618 line:71%
<i> (Dr. Hackney)
 Dance itself is a form of</i>

00:17:32.718 --> 00:17:34.920 line:71%
<i> cognitive rehabilitation.</i>

00:17:35.020 --> 00:17:36.655 line:71%
<i> When people dance,
 and in our--</i>

00:17:36.755 --> 00:17:37.923 line:71%
<i> especially in the tango,
 they have to</i>

00:17:38.023 --> 00:17:41.560 line:71%
<i> use their brains in a very,
 very particular way.</i>

00:17:41.660 --> 00:17:42.895 line:71%
They have to
remember things.

00:17:42.995 --> 00:17:44.296 line:71%
They have to
understand timing.

00:17:44.396 --> 00:17:47.266 line:71%
They have to understand
how to put a movement to music,

00:17:47.366 --> 00:17:49.968 line:71%
and it, in a way, it's
a form of cognitive training.

00:17:50.069 --> 00:17:53.972 line:71%
And I think, if we can see that
on-- in our brain,

00:17:54.073 --> 00:17:55.574 line:71%
that'd be really cool.

00:17:55.674 --> 00:17:57.876 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 It's not just that it works.</i>

00:17:57.976 --> 00:18:02.247 line:71%
<i> It's that this class
 makes people feel good.</i>

00:18:02.347 --> 00:18:04.716 line:68%
<i> (Dr. Hackney)
 It's not about people being
 patients in the room.</i>

00:18:04.817 --> 00:18:06.885 line:71%
<i> It's just about people being
 people together</i>

00:18:06.985 --> 00:18:08.987 line:71%
<i> and enjoying
 something together.</i>

00:18:10.089 --> 00:18:11.723 line:71%
<i> (Jaye)
 For one couple, it continues</i>

00:18:11.824 --> 00:18:15.894 line:71%
<i>what began in a Cincinnati disco
all those years ago.</i>

00:18:15.994 --> 00:18:19.865 line:71%
<i> Dance cannot undo the loss,
 but it can restore</i>

00:18:19.965 --> 00:18:24.436 line:71%
<i> confidence and connection
 step by step.</i>

00:18:24.536 --> 00:18:32.144 line:0%
♪♪

00:18:32.244 --> 00:18:34.646 line:71%
We all have deadlines.
Whether it's a work project,

00:18:34.746 --> 00:18:37.516 line:71%
emails to return,
laundry to get done.

00:18:37.616 --> 00:18:39.017 line:71%
<i> So, then why do we stalk
 high school friends</i>

00:18:39.118 --> 00:18:41.286 line:71%
<i> on Facebook for two hours?</i>

00:18:41.386 --> 00:18:43.255 line:71%
<i> Why do we go to the fridge
 for the fifth time</i>

00:18:43.355 --> 00:18:45.324 line:71%
<i> thinking we'll see something
 we didn't see before?</i>

00:18:45.424 --> 00:18:48.060 line:71%
The reason?
Procrastination.

00:18:48.160 --> 00:18:50.829 line:71%
And here's one definition:
the voluntary delay

00:18:50.929 --> 00:18:53.432 line:71%
<i> of a task we intend to do</i>

00:18:53.532 --> 00:18:56.201 line:71%
<i> and know that we'll suffer
 as a result.</i>

00:18:56.301 --> 00:18:58.904 line:71%
<i> In a study in the journal
 "Psychological Science,"</i>

00:18:59.004 --> 00:19:01.740 line:0%
<i> they've shown that
 procrastination tends
 to run in families.</i>

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:05.244 line:0%
<i> It is in our very genes.
 But, even if we don't</i>

00:19:05.344 --> 00:19:08.180 line:71%
<i> inherit it, most of us
 tend to put stuff off,</i>

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:09.848 line:71%
and that's because
we care more about

00:19:09.948 --> 00:19:11.917 line:71%
the present than the future.

00:19:12.017 --> 00:19:13.952 line:71%
That's the way we're wired
as human beings.

00:19:14.052 --> 00:19:17.156 line:71%
The present is now.
Eh, I'll worry about now.

00:19:17.256 --> 00:19:19.892 line:71%
<i>So, here's advice for next time
you're procrastinating.</i>

00:19:19.992 --> 00:19:21.894 line:71%
<i> Take a step back from
 your life and look at</i>

00:19:21.994 --> 00:19:24.863 line:71%
<i> the big picture,
 what you've been putting off,</i>

00:19:24.963 --> 00:19:29.201 line:71%
<i> going back to school,
 exercising, laundry.</i>

00:19:29.301 --> 00:19:31.470 line:71%
<i> And then comes
 the hard part.</i>

00:19:31.570 --> 00:19:33.438 line:71%
Do it.

00:19:33.539 --> 00:19:35.040 line:71%
Now, to something
all of us do

00:19:35.140 --> 00:19:39.077 line:71%
and probably rarely
consider: blinking.

00:19:39.178 --> 00:19:40.212 line:71%
Scientists say we blink

00:19:40.312 --> 00:19:43.515 line:71%
on average 15 to 20 times
per minute.

00:19:43.615 --> 00:19:45.751 line:71%
That's 1,200 times per hour

00:19:45.851 --> 00:19:49.154 line:71%
and 28,800 times per day.

00:19:49.254 --> 00:19:51.723 line:71%
But, for thousands of people,
the blinking gets

00:19:51.823 --> 00:19:55.694 line:71%
out of control, leaving them
functionally blind.

00:19:55.794 --> 00:19:59.464 line:57%
The rare neurological disorder
is called blepharospasm.

00:19:59.565 --> 00:20:01.466 line:57%
Here's one woman's story.

00:20:02.501 --> 00:20:03.702 line:71%
(Nilda Rendino)
You know, when you're young,

00:20:03.802 --> 00:20:05.671 line:71%
you're young, and
