(Jaye)
This was Nilda when she arrived
at Emory Brain Health,

00:20:59.758 --> 00:21:02.894 line:71%
a 75-year-old woman who
had been living her life

00:21:02.995 --> 00:21:06.431 line:71%
with her eyes closed
most of the time.

00:21:06.531 --> 00:21:08.667 line:68%
<i> (Dr. Hyder Jinnah)
 Um, and so it can be
 extremely disabling.</i>

00:21:08.767 --> 00:21:11.069 line:71%
<i> Um, in fact, when it gets
 bad enough, we call--</i>

00:21:11.169 --> 00:21:13.805 line:71%
<i> we say that people can be
 functionally blind</i>

00:21:13.905 --> 00:21:16.174 line:71%
<i> because they can't
 keep their eyes open.</i>

00:21:16.275 --> 00:21:18.243 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 What is happening to
 Nilda's eyes and face</i>

00:21:18.343 --> 00:21:21.580 line:71%
<i> in this video, the spasms,
 the blinking, the eyes</i>

00:21:21.680 --> 00:21:24.016 line:71%
<i> that won't open, is
 due to a condition</i>

00:21:24.116 --> 00:21:25.984 line:71%
<i> called blepharospasm.</i>

00:21:26.084 --> 00:21:28.620 line:71%
<i> Emory Brain Health's
 Dr. Hyder Jinnah.</i>

00:21:28.720 --> 00:21:32.190 line:57%
In blepharospasm, the muscles
surrounding the eyes

00:21:32.291 --> 00:21:34.259 line:57%
are over-contracting,
so they are doing

00:21:34.359 --> 00:21:36.161 line:57%
more than they should,
but the problem

00:21:36.261 --> 00:21:37.963 line:57%
is not in the muscles.
The problem is actually

00:21:38.063 --> 00:21:41.433 line:57%
in the brain's way of
controlling your blinking.

00:21:41.533 --> 00:21:44.936 line:71%
<i> Somewhere along the line,
 the brain sends signals</i>

00:21:45.037 --> 00:21:47.139 line:71%
<i> for your blinking
 that are too much.</i>

00:21:47.239 --> 00:21:49.274 line:71%
<i> They're too exaggerated
 in some way,</i>

00:21:49.374 --> 00:21:52.511 line:71%
and so you blink longer,
you spasm, uh,

00:21:52.611 --> 00:21:54.446 line:71%
and your eyes may blink closed,
and they don't

00:21:54.546 --> 00:21:57.949 line:71%
open for you like, uh,
in Nilda's case.

00:21:58.050 --> 00:22:00.352 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Nilda was diagnosed
 20 years ago.</i>

00:22:00.452 --> 00:22:03.889 line:71%
<i> That was after six years
 of going doctor to doctor,</i>

00:22:03.989 --> 00:22:06.525 line:71%
<i> after giving up
 driving, and reading,</i>

00:22:06.625 --> 00:22:08.327 line:71%
<i> and even watching TV.</i>

00:22:08.427 --> 00:22:11.396 line:57%
And I was lucky because
people who went through

00:22:11.496 --> 00:22:14.299 line:57%
that same situation
were often told

00:22:14.399 --> 00:22:15.934 line:57%
that it was
in their head

00:22:16.034 --> 00:22:18.170 line:57%
and not meaning that
it was neurological

00:22:18.270 --> 00:22:19.504 line:57%
but that they were--

00:22:19.604 --> 00:22:22.007 line:57%
you know, had
psychological problems.

00:22:22.107 --> 00:22:25.077 line:71%
Some people were
hospitalized

00:22:25.177 --> 00:22:28.513 line:71%
for their, um,
mental problems.

00:22:28.613 --> 00:22:29.781 line:68%
<i> (doctor)
 Next thing
 I want you to do--</i>

00:22:29.881 --> 00:22:32.651 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 A rare condition without
 a known cause or cure,</i>

00:22:32.751 --> 00:22:36.521 line:71%
<i> blepharospasm usually begins
 sometime after the age of 50,</i>

00:22:36.621 --> 00:22:39.691 line:71%
<i> affecting 40,000
 to 50,000 in the U.S.</i>

00:22:39.791 --> 00:22:41.493 line:71%
<i> with twice as many
 as that</i>

00:22:41.593 --> 00:22:44.963 line:57%
<i> thought to be misdiagnosed
 or undiagnosed.</i>

00:22:45.063 --> 00:22:47.966 line:57%
<i> When she finally found out
 what she had 20 years ago</i>

00:22:48.066 --> 00:22:49.468 line:57%
<i> from a doctor up North,</i>

00:22:49.568 --> 00:22:52.471 line:57%
<i> Nilda remembers when
 he told her the treatment.</i>

00:22:52.571 --> 00:22:57.376 line:68%
And he said, "Well,
you get, uh, injections
around your eyes,"

00:22:57.476 --> 00:22:59.778 line:71%
and I said,
"That's the good news?"

00:22:59.878 --> 00:23:01.947 line:71%
The treatment
is botulinum toxin,

00:23:02.047 --> 00:23:05.917 line:71%
and the way it works
is by, um, getting into

00:23:06.017 --> 00:23:08.620 line:71%
the areas where the nerves
control the muscles,

00:23:08.720 --> 00:23:11.590 line:71%
and what it does is,
it slows the nerves down.

00:23:11.690 --> 00:23:13.392 line:71%
It doesn't really
paralyze them.

00:23:13.492 --> 00:23:16.194 line:57%
Um, it slows them down
so that their communication

00:23:16.294 --> 00:23:19.531 line:57%
<i> with the muscles they control
 is less forceful, if you will.</i>

00:23:19.631 --> 00:23:20.832 line:64%
<i> (knocking)</i>

00:23:20.932 --> 00:23:23.435 line:57%
<i> I tell patients that it's
 like a local muscle relaxer.</i>

00:23:23.535 --> 00:23:26.238 line:57%
<i> Um, that's a little
 bit simplified,</i>

00:23:26.338 --> 00:23:27.706 line:71%
<i> but that's really
 what it's doing.</i>

00:23:27.806 --> 00:23:31.777 line:71%
<i> It's working locally to calm
 the overactive muscles.</i>

00:23:31.877 --> 00:23:35.647 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 Botox is the most well-known
 brand of botulinum toxins.</i>

00:23:35.747 --> 00:23:39.184 line:71%
<i> While injections help
 the spasms, for 20 years,</i>

00:23:39.284 --> 00:23:42.487 line:71%
<i> Nilda's eyes still stayed
 closed most of the time</i>

00:23:42.587 --> 00:23:45.490 line:71%
<i> until her husband, Ron,
 drove her to see Dr. Jinnah</i>

00:23:45.590 --> 00:23:47.325 line:71%
<i> from their home
 in North Carolina.</i>

00:23:47.426 --> 00:23:49.661 line:57%
She has also a feature
of blepharospasm

00:23:49.761 --> 00:23:52.330 line:57%
that maybe only 10%
of the patients have,

00:23:52.431 --> 00:23:55.233 line:57%
and that's called
apraxia of eyelid opening.

00:23:55.333 --> 00:23:58.503 line:71%
The eyes close, and then they
won't open by themselves,

00:23:58.603 --> 00:24:00.605 line:71%
and the reason for that is
because there's a spasm

00:24:00.705 --> 00:24:02.474 line:71%
in the skinny muscle
of your eyelid

00:24:02.574 --> 00:24:03.708 line:71%
that goes
right across here,

00:24:03.809 --> 00:24:06.344 line:71%
and if that spasms
while the eyes are closed,

00:24:06.445 --> 00:24:08.580 line:71%
it can't roll up
over your eyeball.

00:24:08.680 --> 00:24:11.450 line:68%
<i> (Jaye)
 A few months ago,
 Jinnah changed the way</i>

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:15.487 line:71%
<i> she had been injected
 and included Nilda's eyelids.</i>

00:24:15.587 --> 00:24:18.156 line:71%
<i> The results have
 been life-changing.</i>

00:24:18.256 --> 00:24:21.259 line:57%
And it's been,
like, unbelievable.

00:24:21.359 --> 00:24:22.794 line:64%
Unbelievable.

00:24:22.894 --> 00:24:25.197 line:57%
My neighbors, who are used
to seeing me going around

00:24:25.297 --> 00:24:27.732 line:57%
with a visor and
sunglasses all the time,

00:24:27.833 --> 00:24:29.401 line:71%
didn't know I had
eyes, you know?

00:24:29.501 --> 00:24:31.236 line:71%
They said,
"Oh, your eyes are open."

00:24:31.336 --> 00:24:33.071 line:71%
I said, "Yes,
my eyes are open."

00:24:33.171 --> 00:24:34.906 line:68%
(Jaye)
We were with Nilda
three months after

00:24:35.006 --> 00:24:37.242 line:71%
her newly altered
injection plan.

